<Author>A TripAdvisor Member
<Content>Off the Beaten Track My husband and I stayed at Hotel Morandi October 25-30, 2004. We had to haul our luggage up two long flights of marble stairs from the street to reach the entrance of the hotel. Our room (25) was beautifully furnished in the style of the old convent, and there was room for a couch and chairs. At that time the management was testing a free internet service with terminals in each room. The bathroom was spacious with a tub, a treat for a tired tourist who desires a good soak. The room had one large window that overlooked a small courtyard, but it was difficult to open the outside shutters to let in the light, leaving me feeling a little closed in. Also, the whole place is locked on the street and at the front door from 9 pm until early the next morning. There is no staff there at night, though we were given a phone number to call in case of emergency. We did not eat breakfast there, as it was an additional E11.The hotel is on a small, unattractive street that is busy during the day but quiet at night. However, it is several blocks' walking distance before you get to streets and piazzas that have restaurants and stores. In October, it was dark when we went out for dinner, and we didn't want to walk very far, thus limiting our choice of restaurants, which we felt was not that good in that neighborhood. Also, being a bit away from the centers of interest (between the Duomo and the river) required that we walk a little farther each day before we could take in the wonderful museums and sights.The hotel was unusual, the room comfortable, and the staff pleasant and helpful. However, if we visit Florence again, I would look for a room closer to the center of the city. 
